\section{Part 1}

Solve the following exercises from the book (Huth \& Ryan, Logic in Computer
Science, Second Edition):

\begin{enumerate}
\item Page 78 1.1.1

Use $\lnot$, $\to$, $\land$ and $\lor$ to express the following declarative
sentences in propositional logic; in each case state what your respective
propositional atoms $p$, $q$, etc. mean

  \begin{itemize}
  \item[a)] If the sun shines today, then it won't shine tomorrow. \\
    $p$: The sun shines today \\
    $q$: The sun will shine tomorrow
    \[p \to \lnot q\] \\

  \item[d)] If a request occurs, then either it will eventually be acknowledged,
    or the requesting process won’t ever be able to make progress. \\
    $p$: A request occurs \\
    $q$: The request is acknowledged \\
    $r$: The requesting process will be able to make progress
    \[p \to (q \lor r)\] \\

  \item[i)] If Dick met Jane yesterday, they had a cup of coﬀee together, or
    they took a walk in the park. \\
    $p$: Dick met Jane yesterday \\
    $q$: Dick and Jane had a cup of coffee together \\
    $r$: Dick and Jane took a walk in the park
    \[p \to (q \lor r)\] \\
  \end{itemize}

  \pagebreak

\item Page 78 1.2.1 \\
  Prove the validity of the following sequents:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item[c)] $(p \land q) \land r \vdash p \land (q \land r)$ \\
    \begin{logicproof}{0}
      (p \land q) \land r & premise \\
      p \land q & $\land e_1 \ 1$ \\
      r & $\land e_2 \ 1$ \\
      p & $\land e_1 \ 2$ \\
      q & $\land e_2 \ 2$ \\
      q \land r & $\land i \ 5, 3$ \\
      p \land (q \land r) & $\land i \ 4, 6$
    \end{logicproof}

  \item[f)] $\vdash (p \land q) \to p$ \\
    \begin{logicproof}{1}
      \begin{subproof}
        p \land q & assumption \\
        p & $\land e_1 \ 1$
      \end{subproof}
      (p \land q) \to p & $\to i \ 1 \textrm - 2$
    \end{logicproof}

  \item[r)] $p \to q \land r \vdash (p \to q) \land (p \to r)$ \\
    \begin{logicproof}{1}
      p \to q \land r & premise \\
      \begin{subproof}
        p & assumption \\
        p \to q \land r & copy 1 \\
        q \land r & $\to e \ 2, 3$ \\
        q & $\land e_1 \ 4 $
      \end{subproof}
      p \to q & $\to i \ 2 \textrm - 5$ \\
      \begin{subproof}
        p & assumption \\
        p \to q \land r & copy 1 \\
        q \land r & $\to e \ 7, 8$ \\
        r & $\land e_2 \ 9$
      \end{subproof}
      p \to r & $\to i \ 7 \textrm - 10$ \\
      (p \to q) \land (p \to r) & $\to i \ 6, 11$
    \end{logicproof}
  \end{itemize}

\pagebreak
\item Page 79 1.2.2 \\
  For the sequents below, show which ones are valid and which ones aren’t:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item[b)] $\lnot p \lor \lnot q \vdash \lnot (p \land q)$ \\
    \begin{logicproof}{2}
      \lnot p \lor \lnot q & premise \\
      \begin{subproof}
        p \land q & assumption \\
        \lnot p \lor \lnot q & copy 1 \\
        \begin{subproof}
          \lnot p & assumption \\
          p & $\land e_1 \ 2$ \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 4, 5$
        \end{subproof}
        \begin{subproof}
          \lnot q & assumption \\
          q & $\land e_2 \ 2$ \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 7, 8$
        \end{subproof}
        \bot & $\lor e \ 3, 4 \textrm - 6, 7 \textrm - 9$
      \end{subproof}
      \lnot(p \land q) & $\lnot i 2 \textrm - 10$
    \end{logicproof}

    The argument $\lnot p \lor \lnot q \vdash \lnot (p \land q)$ is thus valid.
    \\

  \item[c)] $\lnot p, p \lor q \vdash q$ \\
    \begin{logicproof}{2}
      \lnot p & premise \\
      p \lor q & premise \\
      \begin{subproof}
        \lnot q & assumption \\
        p \lor q & copy 2 \\
        \begin{subproof}
          p & assumption \\
          \lnot p & copy 1 \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 5, 6$
        \end{subproof}
        \begin{subproof}
          q & assumption \\
          \lnot q & copy 3 \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 8, 9$
        \end{subproof}
        \bot & $\lor e \ 4, 5 \textrm - 7, 8 \textrm - 10$
      \end{subproof}
      q & PBC 3-11
    \end{logicproof}
    The argument $\lnot p, p \lor q \vdash q$ is thus valid.
  \end{itemize}

  \pagebreak
\item page 81 1.3.1 \\
  Given the following formulas, produce their corresponding SMT-LIB encoding.
  \begin{itemize}
  \item[c)] $p \land \lnot q \to \lnot p$ \\
    \begin{lstlisting}
      (declare-const p Bool)
      (declare-const q Bool)

      (assert
        (=>
          (and p (not q))
          (not p)))
    \end{lstlisting}

  \item[h)] $(p \land q) \to (\lnot r \lor (q \to r))$
  \item[j)] $(s \lor ((\lnot p) \to (\lnot p)))$
  \item[k)] $(((s \to (r \lor l)) \lor ((\lnot q) \land r)) \to
    ((\lnot (p \to s)) \to r))$
  \end{itemize}

  \pagebreak
\item page 82 1.3.5 \\
  For the parse tree in Figure 1.22 find the logical formula it represents.

  \renewcommand{\thefigure}{1.22}
  \begin{figure}[h!]
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}[nodes = {draw, circle}, -]
      \node{$\lnot$}
      child { node {$\to$} 
        child { node {$\lnot$}
          child { node {$\lor$}
            child { node {$p$} }
            child { node {$\land$}
              child { node {$q$} }
              child { node {$\lnot$}
                child { node {$p$} }
              }
            }
          }
        }
        child { node {$r$} }
      };
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{A parse tree of a negated implication.}
  \end{figure}

  Starting from the root of the tree, we can determine the associated logical
  formula to be as such:
  \[\lnot ((\lnot (p \lor (q \land \lnot p))) \to r)\]
  
  \pagebreak
\item page 87 1.4.17 \\
  Does $\vDash \phi$ hold for the $\phi$ below? Please justify your answer.
  \begin{itemize}
  \item[a)] $(p \to q) \lor (q \to r)$ \\
    Because propositional logic is \textbf{sound}, if it can be shown that a
    proof exists for $\vdash (p \to q) \lor (q \to r)$, then it can be inferred
    that $\vDash (p \to q) \lor (q \to r)$ holds.

    Below is such a proof:
    
    \begin{logicproof}{3}
      \begin{subproof}
        \lnot ((p \to q) \lor (q \to r)) & assumption \\
        \begin{subproof}
          \lnot (\lnot (p \to q) \land \lnot (q \to r)) & assumption \\
          \begin{subproof}
            p \to q & assumption \\
            (p \to q) \lor (q \to r) & $\lor i_1 \ 3$ \\
            \lnot ((p \to q) \lor (q \to r)) & copy 1 \\
            \bot & $\lnot e \ 4, 5$
          \end{subproof}
          \lnot (p \to q) & $\lnot i \ 3 \textrm - 6$ \\
          \begin{subproof}
            q \to r & assumption \\
            (p \to q) \lor (q \to r) & $\lor i_2 \ 8$ \\
            \lnot ((p \to q) \lor (q \to r)) & copy 1 \\
            \bot & $\lnot e \ 9, 10$
          \end{subproof}
          \lnot (q \to r) & $\lnot i \ 8 \textrm - 11$ \\
          (\lnot (p \to q)) \land (\lnot (q \to r)) & $\land i \ 7, 12$ \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 2, 13$
        \end{subproof}
        \lnot (p \to q) \land \lnot (q \to r) & PBC 2-14 \\
        \begin{subproof}
          q & assumption \\
          \begin{subproof}
            p & assumption \\
            q & copy 16
          \end{subproof}
          p \to q & $\to i \ 17, 18$ \\
          \lnot (p \to q) & $\land e_1 \ 15$ \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 19, 20$
        \end{subproof}
        \lnot q & $\lnot i \ 16 \textrm - 21$ \\
        \begin{subproof}
          \lnot q & assumption \\
          \begin{subproof}
            \lnot r & assumption \\
            \lnot q & copy 23
          \end{subproof}
          \lnot r \to \lnot q & $\to i \ 24, 25$ \\
          \begin{subproof}
            q & assumption \\
            \lnot \lnot q & $\lnot \lnot i \ 27$ \\
            \lnot \lnot r & MT 27, 28 \\
            r & $\lnot \lnot e \ 29$
          \end{subproof}
          q \to r & $\to i \ 27 \textrm - 30$ \\
          \lnot (q \to r) & $\land e_2 \ 15$ \\
          \bot & $\lnot e \ 31, 32$
        \end{subproof}
        q & PBC 23-33 \\
        \bot & $\lnot e \ 22, 34$
      \end{subproof}
      (p \to q) \lor (q \to r) & PBC 1-35
    \end{logicproof}

    \pagebreak
  \item[b)] $((q \to (p \lor (q \to p))) \lor \lnot (p \to q)) \to p$ \\
    By using a truth table approach, an assignment for the elementary
    propositions can be determined to construct a counter-example for this
    formula (the bolded truth values indicate the truth values of the overall
    formula under its line assignment):

    \begin{center}
      \begin{tabular}{| c | c || c c c c c c c c c |}
        \hline
        $p$ & $q$ & $((q$ & $\to$ & $(p \lor (q \to p)))$ & $\lor$
        & $\lnot (p$ & $\to$ & $q))$ & $\to$ & $p$ \\
        [0.5ex]
        \hline
        \hline
        $\top$ & $\top$ & & $\top$ & & $\top$ & & $\bot$& & $\pmb{\top}$ & \\
        \hline
        $\top$ & $\bot$ & & $\top$ & & $\top$ & & $\top$& & $\pmb{\top}$ & \\
        \hline
        $\bot$ & $\top$ & & $\bot$ & & $\bot$ & & $\bot$& & $\pmb{\top}$ & \\
        \hline
        $\bot$ & $\bot$ & & $\top$ & & $\top$ & & $\bot$& & $\pmb{\bot}$ & \\
        \hline
      \end{tabular}
    \end{center}

    The counter-example is thus defined with the following assignment:
    $\alpha(p) = \bot$ and $\alpha(q) = \bot$ under which the formula becomes
    false also thus meaning that
    $\vDash ((q \to (p \lor (q \to p))) \lor \lnot (p \to q)) \to p$ does not
    hold.
  \end{itemize}

  \pagebreak
\item Page 89 1.5.15 \\
  Apply algorithm \texttt{HORN} from page 66 to each of these Horn formulas:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item[a)] $(p \land q \land w \to \bot) \land (t \to \bot) \land (r \to p)
    \land (\top \to r) \land (\top \to q) \land (u \to s) \land (\top \to u)$ \\
  \item[g)] $(\top \to q) \land (\top \to s) \land (w \to \bot) \land (p \land q
    \land s \to v) \land (v \to s) \land (\top \to r) \land (r \to p)$ \\
  \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

